[{"id":"VH967199","type":"mcq","stimulusHtml":"<div><include href=\"../Passage/VH967196.qti.xml\" xmlns:xi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude\"></include></div><p class=\"stem_paragraph\">A small particle with a charge of magnitude <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"q\"><math alttext=\"q\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>q</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> is released from rest at point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>B</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and moves until it hits point <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mtext>A</mtext></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. If the potential difference <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"delta V\"><math alttext=\"delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> between the plates is known, which of the following correctly explains a method to determine the increase in kinetic energy of the particle?</p>\n","rubricRef":"VH967199_rubric","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<div class=\"stimulus_reference\" xmlns=\"http://www.imsglobal.org/xsd/apip/apipv1p0/qtiitem/imsqti_v2p2\" xmlns:xsi=\"http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance\">\n<div class=\"passage\">\n<div class=\"prose style:1\">\n<div class=\"standalone_image\"><img alt=\"The figure presents a diagram of a sphere on an insulating stand, with a positive charge uniformly distributed throughout. The sphere is located at a distance of L to the right of two vertical, parallel conducting plates. The conducting plates are located at a distance of d apart. Point A is shown in the middle of the left vertical plate and point B is shown in the middle of the right vertical plate.\" height=\"144\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/VH967196.g01.png\" width=\"220\" /></div>\n\n<p class=\"passage_para\">Students perform an experiment using the setup shown in the figure. A sphere with uniform charge distribution on an insulating stand is placed a distance from parallel uncharged conducting plates separated by a fixed distance <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"d\"><math alttext=\"d\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span>. Points <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"A\"><math alttext=\"A\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> and <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"B\"><math alttext=\"B\" overflow=\"scroll\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>B</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> are labeled.</p>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div>\n"}],"choicesHtml":["<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Use <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"q delta V\"><math alttext=\"q delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> to determine the decrease in the potential energy of the plates-particle system. That is equal to the increase in the kinetic energy of the particle.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Use <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction q delta V, over d\"><math alttext=\"the fraction q delta V, over d\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mstyle><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math></span></span> to determine the decrease in the potential energy of the plates-particle system. That is equal to the increase in the kinetic energy of the particle.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Use <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"q delta V\"><math alttext=\"q delta V\" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mstyle><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mstyle></math></span></span> to determine the work done by an external force on the plates-particle system. That is equal to the increase in the kinetic energy of the particle.</p>","<p class=\"choice_paragraph\">Use <span class=\"math_expression\"><span aria-label=\"the fraction q delta V, over d \"><math alttext=\"the fraction q delta V, over d \" display=\"inline\" overflow=\"scroll\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mstyle><mrow><mi>q</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mi>V</mi></mrow></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math></span></span> to determine the work done by an external force on the plates-particle system. That is equal to the increase in the kinetic energy of the particle.</p>"],"answer":0}]